rteen game theorists to submit computer programs with the algorithm of thei=
r choice; Axelrod described the winner in The Evolution of Cooperation:

TIT FOR TAT, submitted by Professor Anatol Rapoport of the University of To=
ronto, won the tournament. This was the simplest of all submitted programs =
and it turned out to be the best! TIT FOR TAT, of course, starts with a coo=
perative choice, and thereafter does what the other player did on the previ=
ous move=E2=80=A6

Analysis of the results showed that neither the discipline of the author, t=
